**Optional parameters** use `?` and may or may not be provided. If not provided, they are `undefined`:

```typescript
function greet(name: string, greeting?: string): string {
    return greeting ? `${greeting}, ${name}!` : `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

greet("Alice");            // "Hello, Alice!" (greeting is undefined)
greet("Alice", "Welcome"); // "Welcome, Alice!"
```

**Default parameters** provide a fallback value if the argument is not provided:

```typescript
function greet(name: string, greeting: string = "Hello"): string {
    return `${greeting}, ${name}!`;
}

greet("Alice");            // "Hello, Alice!" (uses default)
greet("Alice", "Welcome"); // "Welcome, Alice!"
```

**When to use each:**

- **Optional parameters**: When the absence of a value is meaningful and you want to handle it explicitly (e.g., checking if a filter was provided)
- **Default parameters**: When you want a sensible fallback value without extra conditional logic

**Key difference:** Optional parameters can be `undefined`, default parameters always have a value.

**Union Types (`|`)** — A value can be **ONE of several types**:

```typescript
type ID = string | number;

let userId: ID = 123;       // ✅ number
userId = "ABC123";          // ✅ string

// Use case: When a value can have different types
type Status = "pending" | "approved" | "rejected";
type ApiResult = Success | Error;
```

**Intersection Types (`&`)** — A value must have **ALL properties from ALL types**:

```typescript
interface Person {
    name: string;
    age: number;
}

interface Employee {
    employeeId: number;
    department: string;
}

type EmployeePerson = Person & Employee;

const emp: EmployeePerson = {
    name: "Alice",
    age: 30,
    employeeId: 12345,
    department: "Engineering"
};
```

**When to use:**

- **Union**: When a value can be one of several distinct types (API responses, function parameters that accept multiple types)
- **Intersection**: When combining multiple interfaces/types into one (mixins, extending objects with additional properties)

**Simple rule:**
- `|` = OR (one of these)
- `&` = AND (all of these)

```typescript
// Base interface
interface Product {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    price: number;
    description?: string;  // Optional
}

// Extended interface for digital products
interface DigitalProduct extends Product {
    downloadUrl: string;
    fileSize: number;        // in MB
    format: "pdf" | "mp4" | "zip";
}

// Function that accepts any Product (including DigitalProduct)
function displayProduct(product: Product): void {
    console.log(`${product.name} - $${product.price}`);
    if (product.description) {
        console.log(`Description: ${product.description}`);
    }
}

// Usage with base Product
const laptop: Product = {
    id: 1,
    name: "MacBook Pro",
    price: 1999,
    description: "Powerful laptop"
};

// Usage with DigitalProduct (also valid as Product)
const ebook: DigitalProduct = {
    id: 2,
    name: "TypeScript Guide",
    price: 29.99,
    downloadUrl: "https://example.com/ts-guide.pdf",
    fileSize: 15,
    format: "pdf"
};

displayProduct(laptop);  // ✅ Works
displayProduct(ebook);   // ✅ Works (DigitalProduct extends Product)
```

Extending interfaces allows you to build specialized types while maintaining compatibility with functions that accept the base type.

**`Partial<T>`** — Makes ALL properties optional:

```typescript
interface User {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    email: string;
}

// For updating users (only update some fields)
function updateUser(id: number, updates: Partial<User>): void {
    // updates can have any combination of User properties
}

updateUser(1, { name: "Alice" });  // ✅ Only updating name
updateUser(2, { email: "new@email.com", name: "Bob" });  // ✅ Multiple fields
```

**`Pick<T, K>`** — Creates type with ONLY specified properties:

```typescript
// For API responses that shouldn't expose everything
type PublicUser = Pick<User, "id" | "name">;
// { id: number; name: string; }

function getPublicProfile(id: number): PublicUser {
    return { id, name: "Alice" };  // No email exposed
}
```

**`Omit<T, K>`** — Creates type WITHOUT specified properties:

```typescript
interface User {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    email: string;
    password: string;  // Sensitive!
}

// Remove sensitive data
type SafeUser = Omit<User, "password">;
// { id: number; name: string; email: string; }

// For creating new users (id generated by server)
type CreateUser = Omit<User, "id">;
// { name: string; email: string; password: string; }
```

**Summary:**
- `Partial`: Update operations (some fields)
- `Pick`: Select specific fields (public APIs)
- `Omit`: Exclude fields (remove sensitive data, create operations)

**Type assertions** tell TypeScript: "Trust me, I know this type is correct." They use the `as` keyword:

```typescript
// DOM elements - TypeScript doesn't know the specific type
const input = document.getElementById("email") as HTMLInputElement;
input.value = "test@example.com";  // Now we can access .value

// API responses when you know the structure
const user = await response.json() as User;
```

**When to use them:**
1. DOM element access (TypeScript can't know element types)
2. API responses with known structure
3. When narrowing from a broader type you're certain about

**Dangers of overusing:**

```typescript
// ❌ DANGEROUS: Lying to TypeScript
const value: string = "hello";
const num = value as unknown as number;
num.toFixed(2);  // Runtime crash! "hello" is not a number

// ❌ BAD: Asserting instead of validating
function process(data: unknown) {
    const user = data as User;  // No validation!
    console.log(user.name);     // Might crash
}

// ✅ GOOD: Validate first
function process(data: unknown) {
    if (isUser(data)) {
        console.log(data.name);  // Safe
    }
}
```

**Best practices:**
1. Use type guards/validation when possible
2. Only assert when you're 100% certain of the type
3. Avoid `as unknown as X` — it bypasses all safety
4. If you're asserting frequently, reconsider your types
